		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2024 SI"></a><br><code>sle2024s/paper02</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2024 SI</a> paper:</span><br><i>Supporting reusable model migration with Edelta</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/LorenzoBettini.html">Lorenzo Bettini</a>, <a href="../profile/AmletoDiSalle.html">Amleto Di Salle</a>, <a href="../profile/LudovicoIovino.html">Ludovico Iovino</a>, <a href="../profile/AlfonsoPierantonio.html">Alfonso Pierantonio</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jss.2024.112012">10.1016/j.jss.2024.112012</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagM">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> The work targets model/metamodel evolution, specifically supporting model migration across evolving metamodels.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagL">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> Edelta is presented as a dedicated language for specifying migrations/operations (i.e., transformation specifications) in a reusable way.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The contribution includes tooling/framework support to automate and apply migrations in a language engineering ecosystem.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1e.html"><span class="tagL">T1E: Reuse</span></a><ul><li> Emphasis is on reusable migration building blocks/operators that can be applied across multiple evolution scenarios.
</li></ul></li></ul>
